9","1400–1461":"1400–1461","1410–1461":"1410–1461","1340–1399":"1340–1399","1355–1380":"1355–1380","2 April 1375":"2 april 1375","1400":"1400","1399":"1399","1410":"1410","1355":"1355","1375":"1375","1385":"1385","1340":"1340","1461":"1461","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1429":"1429","Glassenbury, Kent, England":"Glassenbury, Kent, England","Maidstone, Kent, England":"Maidstone, Kent, England","Maidstone,Kent,England.":"Maidstone, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","St. Faith's Church, Maidstone, Kent, England":"Maidstone, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Thirsk, North Yorkshire, England":"Thirsk, North Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"2 April 1375–1429":"2 April 1375–1429","1375–1429":"1375–1429","1385–1429":"1385–1429","1400–1461":"1400–1461","1410–1461":"1410–1461","1340–1399":"1340–1399","1355–1380":"1355–1380","2 April 1375":"2 April 1375","1400":"1400","1399":"1399","1410":"1410","1355":"1355","1375":"1375","1385":"1385","1340":"1340","1461":"1461","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1429":"1429","Glassenbury, Kent, England":"Glassenbury, Kent, England","Maidstone, Kent, England":"Maidstone, Kent, England","Maidstone,Kent,England.":"Maidstone, Kent, England, United Kingdom","St. Faith's Church, Maidstone, Kent, England":"Maidstone, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Thirsk, North Yorkshire, England":"Thirsk, North Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (northern) and Scottish (Lowlands): from the Middle English personal name <i>Bell</i>. As a man's name this is from Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘handsome’, which was also used as a nickname. As a female name it represents a short form of   Isabel  .","English (northern) and Scottish (Lowlands): from Middle English <i>belle</i> ‘bell’ (Old English <i>belle</i>), in various applications; most probably a metonymic occupational name for a bell ringer or bell maker, or a topographic name for someone living ‘at the bell’ (as attested by 14th-century forms such as <i>John atte Belle</i>). This indicates either residence by an actual bell (e.g. a town's bell in a bell tower, centrally placed to summon meetings, sound the alarm, etc.) or ‘at the sign of the bell’, i.e. a house or inn sign (although surnames derived from house and inn signs are rare in Scots and English).","English: from Middle English <i>bel</i> ‘fair, fine, good’ (Old French <i>bel</i> ‘beautiful, fair’). See also   Beal   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Alfonso, Alvarado, Augusto, Belia, Josefina, Juan, Manuel, Mario, Romero, Santa.","French, Spanish, Portuguese, and English (of French origin): from the Old French female personal name <i>Isabel</i>, which is first recorded in late 11th-century Paris and Maine (France). It was an alternative form of   Elizabeth  , Old French <i>Elisabet</i>, which had a shortened pet form <i>Isabet</i>. <i>Isabel</i> appears to have originated as a variant of <i>Isabet</i>, in which the suffix <i>-el</i> was substituted for <i>-et</i> through re-interpretation of <i>-et</i> as a hypocoristic diminutive. The resultant <i>-bel</i> was early associated with Old French <i>bel</i> ‘fair, beautiful’, as is evident in the French variant <i>Isabeau</i>. From France the name was taken to England, where it achieved considerable popularity in the late medieval period as an independent personal name alongside its rarer doublet <i>Elizabeth</i>. In the form <i>Isabel</i> it also appears in Spain and Portugal, while in Italy it took the form   Isabella  . The French surnames <i>Isabel</i> and   Isabelle   are particularly associated with Normandy.","History: Michel Isabel from Reux in Calvados, France, married Marie Jobidon in Château-Richer, QC, in 1673."]},{"name":"Beller","meanings":["English: occupational name for a bell founder or bell ringer, from Middle English <i>beller</i>, an agent derivative of Old English <i>belle</i> ‘bell’. Compare   Bell   2.","German: habitational name for someone from any of several places called Bell in North Rhine-Westphalia or Bellen near Bremen.","German: nickname for a quarreller, from Middle High German <i>bellen</i> ‘to bicker, quarrel’."]},{"name":"Bells","meanings":["English: variant of   Bell   with genitival or excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Bellman","meanings":["English and Scottish: occupational name for a bell ringer, in particular one whose duty was to make public announcements, after ringing a bell to attract attention (from Middle English <i>bel(le)man</i>, a term known to have been used in York and Scotland, and probably elsewhere, for a town crier). Compare   Bell  .","English: occupational name from Middle English <i>beli-man</i> ‘bellows blower’, from Middle English <i>beli</i> ‘bellows’. Compare   Bellow  .","Altered form of German   Bellmann  . This surname is also found in Sweden."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Beale","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Yiddish name probably derived from the Slavic element <i>beli</i> ‘white’, although some believe it to be from the Romance adjective <i>bella</i> ‘beautiful’."],"variants":[{"name":"Beyle.","meanings":["Yiddish name probably derived from the Slavic element <i>beli</i> ‘white’, although some believe it to be from the Romance adjective <i>bella</i> ‘beautiful’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":6,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Beale Bell was born on 2 April 1375, in Maidstone, Kent, England, his father, Sir John Beale, was 35 and his mother, Lady Katherine de Buckfold, was 20. He had at least 2 sons with Catherine Gurnerrfelder. He died in 1429, in his hometown, at the age of 54, and was buried in Maidstone, Kent, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"2 April 1375–1429":"2. aprill 1375–1429","1375–1429":"1375–1429","1385–1429":"1385–1429","1400–1461":"1400–1461","1410–1461":"1410–1461","1340–1399":"1340–1399","1355–1380":"1355–1380","2 April 1375":"2. aprill 1375","1400":"1400","1399":"1399","1410":"1410","1355":"1355","1375":"1375","1385":"1385","1340":"1340","1461":"1461","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1429":"1429","Glassenbury, Kent, England":"Glassenbury, Kent, England","Maidstone, Kent, England":"Maidstone, Kent, England","Maidstone,Kent,England.":"Maidstone, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","St. Faith's Church, Maidstone, Kent, England":"Maidstone, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Thirsk, North Yorkshire, England":"Thirsk, North Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"2 April 1375–1429":"2. huhtikuuta 1375–1429","1375–1429":"1375–1429","1385–1429":"1385–1429","1400–1461":"1400–1461","1410–1461":"1410–1461","1340–1399":"1340–1399"